paragraphs.title: Intro
paragraphs.text:
%md

In this lab we'll cover basics of building a Linear Regression model in Apache Spark. We'll briefly discuss what a model is and specifically what's a Linear Regression model. We'll set up our training data set by either manually creating a DataFrame or reading from a popular libsvm format. We'll train two models using one and two feature data sets. We'll then overlay and visualize the model on top of the training data points, which should give you an intuitive understanding of what the Linear Regression algorithm does. Finally, we'll save the results of our model training.

By the end of this lab you should have learned the basics of an end-to-end flow that could be used to productize models based on real-world multi-feature data sets.

paragraphs.title: What is a model?
paragraphs.text:
%md

A **model** is a **mathematical formula** with a number of parameters that need to be learned from the data. **Fitting a model to the data** is a process known as **model training**.

Take, for instance one feature/variable linear regression, where a goal is to fit a line (described by the well know eqution `y = ax + b`) to a set of distributed data points.

For example, assume that once model training is complete we get a model equation `y = 2x + 5`. Then for a set of inputs `[1, 0, 7, 2, …]` we would get a set of outputs `[7, 5, 19, 9, …]`. That's it!

In this notebook you will get a chance to learn a step-by-step process of training a one and two feature linear regression model with Spark.

paragraphs.title: Why Linear Regression?
paragraphs.text:
%md

We're introducing Machine Learning with **Linear Regression** because it's one of the more basic and **commonly used predictive analytics method**. It's also easy to explain and grasp intuitively as you'll make your way through the examples.

Note, that we will not cover the details of how the underlying Linear Regression algorithm works. We will merely focus on applying the algorithm and generating a model. If you would like to learn more about Linear Regression and other algorithms check out an excellent [Coursera Machine Learning Course](https://www.coursera.org/learn/machine-learning).

paragraphs.title: Datasets? DataFrames?
paragraphs.text:
%md

If you skipped other introductory labs on Spark, it's worth noting what Spark Datasets and DataFrames are.

A **Dataset** is a distributed collection of data. Dataset provides the benefits of strong typing, ability to use powerful lambda functions with the benefits of (Spark SQL’s) optimized execution engine. A Dataset can be constructed from JVM objects and then manipulated using functional transformations (map, flatMap, filter, etc.). The Dataset API is available in Scala and Java.

A **DataFrame** is a Dataset organized into named columns. It is conceptually equivalent to a table in a relational database or a data frame in R/Python, but with richer optimizations under the hood. DataFrames can be constructed from a wide array of sources such as: structured data files, tables in Hive, external databases, or existing RDDs. The DataFrame API is available in Scala, Java, Python, and R. In Scala and Java, a DataFrame is represented by a Dataset of Rows. In the Scala API, DataFrame is simply a type alias of Dataset[Row]. (Note that in Scala type parameters (generics) are enclosed in square brackets.)

Throughout this document, we will often refer to Scala/Java Datasets of Rows as DataFrames. [[source](http://spark.apache.org/docs/2.0.0/sql-programming-guide.html#datasets-and-dataframes)]
